                <description>Change pashta over sin to qadma.</description>
                <lc>
                    <folio>Folio_102A</folio>
                    <column>3</column>
                    <line>24</line>
                    <credit>Credit: Sefaria.org.</credit>
                </lc>
                <reftext>תַעֲשֶֽׂ֙ה־</reftext>
                <refuni>tav     patah     ayin     hataf-patah     shin     sin-dot     segol     pashta     meteg     he     maqaf     </refuni>
                <changetext>תַעֲשֶֽׂ֨ה־</changetext>
                <changeuni>tav     patah     ayin     hataf-patah     shin     sin-dot     segol     qadma     meteg     he     maqaf     </changeuni>
                <notes>
                    <note>This Decalogue text contains double accent, the text is also in poor condition. The mark in question is a broken line coming out of the rightmost leg of the sin. A pashta is post-positive and appears on the left side of the letter. One or two pashtas can occur on a word. If a word has a single pashta, it must occur on the final letter of the word. If a word has two pashtas, one occurs on the final letter and the other acts as an "accent helper" placed over the accented letter. This word has a single, pashta/qadma-like mark over the sin and no corresponding mark on the final letter. Therefore, the mark in question isn't a pashta, but a qadma,</note>
                    <note>BHL has a qadma centered over the sin. (Dotan numbers the division differently than the UXLC and other modern texts. He combines UXLC verses 6 and 7 into a single verse so that UXLC verse 8 is BHL verse 7.)  BHLA has no entry for this verse.</note>
                </notes>
